explanation:
For MISRA C rule checking about const-qualified pointers you must know the exact types and function prototypes used in OS_ForEachObjectOfType so you can determine whether any pointer parameters/fields could or should be const. Specifically:

- OS_ArgCallback_t: gives the signature of the user callback (types of its parameters and whether the callback expects/modifies the callback_arg). Determines if callback_arg could be const.
- OS_creator_filter_t: defines the struct fields (types of creator_id, user_callback, user_arg) and any existing const qualifiers. Needed to know whether user_callback/user_arg are already const-qualified or are modified through the filter.
- OS_ForEachFilterCreator: prototype shows how the filter is passed into the iterator initializer (pointer type and constness) and whether the iterator callback is allowed to modify the filter.
- OS_ForEachDoCallback: prototype shows how the user callback and user_arg are invoked by the iterator processing, and whether the processing function treats the user_arg as mutable or const.
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit: prototype (parameter types and const qualifiers) indicates whether the iterator library will modify the filter or merely read it (i.e., whether the filter pointer could be const) and the exact type of the iterator parameter.
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry: prototype shows how the processing callback is passed and whether it is expected to be a function that mutates data; also the constness of arguments passed to the callback.
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext: prototype indicates whether the iterator object is modified by GetNext (hence whether OS_object_iter_t passed by pointer needs to be non-const) and whether any pointers inside are modified.
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy: prototype to see whether destroy modifies or takes ownership of iterator internals (affects whether iter should be const at points).
- OS_object_iter_t: definition of the iterator type is required to determine which fields are mutable and whether any pointers inside should be const-qualified.
- osal_id_t and osal_objtype_t: underlying typedefs for the id and type parameters (to check if they are pointer types that might require const qualification or if they are scalar types).
- OS_SUCCESS: value used in the conditional; not directly about const but needed to understand control flow (whether iterator init succeeded) which affects whether the filter may be used only for read-only or may be modified.

Providing these symbols (typedefs/structs and function prototypes) lets the next analyzer determine whether pointers passed into OS_ForEachObjectOfType (callback_arg, filter fields, callbacks, iterator) are modified anywhere and therefore whether they should be const-qualified under MISRA guidance.
